uld that still avoid reflection? I'm still pondering this!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering serialization tests**\\n\\nI'm thinking about creating a test focused on serialization roundtrip, but specifically for the JVM. I realize I want to catch MissingReflectionRegistrationError, but I'm not sure if using guards or catches won't work here. I'm curious if I can incorporate dynamic agent hints using JUnit, but that might limit direct metadata options. There's a lot to unpack here, and I'm exploring the best approach to get this done effectively!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering reflection registration**\\n\\nI’m wondering if I need to register the java.lang.Object constructor with `@RegisterForReflection(targetClass = Object.class, methods = true)` in my test code. This would add a reachability hint, but I’m not sure if that's allowed since it's not actual metadata. I think it could potentially mask any missing metadata and affect dynamic coverage. Hmm, I need to think about the implications of doing that!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating Graal dependencies**\\n\\nI need to focus on the java.lang.Object constructor for serialization mechanics rather than on library metadata. There’s also the question of whether adding a Graal annotation requires a dependency, specifically `org.graalvm.nativeimage.hosted.Feature`. That might need to be on the classpath due to the TCK plugin. I think I’ll need to search for RegisterForReflection in the tests to clarify this further.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_ZPlxzuh9u826Ohrov11pFeLD|fc_0eeee9a29c5ed17f016a10c5f2db18819391f82507598f0a9f", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg -n \"RegisterForReflection|SerializationFeature|RuntimeReflection|ObjectInputStream|readObject\\(\" tests/src -g '*.java' | head -100"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1797, "output": 1662, "cacheRead": 30208, "cacheWrite